The above metric is singular at the cosmological horizon, which
divides space into four regions. There are two regions with 
which correspond to the causal diamonds of observers at the north
and south poles : northern diamond (ND) and southern diamond (SD).
An observer at  is surrounded by a cosmological horizon at
.
Two regions with  containing the future-null infinity  and
past-null infinity   are called future triangle (FT)
and past triangle (PT), respectively.
A timelike Killing vector  is
future-directed only in the southern diamond. To obtain the
greybody factor, we have to obtain a definite wave propagation
as  time evolves. Hence in this work we confine ourselves to the southern diamond.
This means that our working space is compact, in contrast to the
case of the black hole. This gave rise to an ambiguity to
derive the greybody factor in the previous approach.

