 absorption cross section 
Up to now we do not
insert the curvature radius  of de Sitter space.
The correct absorption coefficient can be recovered when replacing  with
.
An absorption coefficient by the cosmological horizon is defined formally by
A  =  F _out (z=1) F _out (z=0) .
However, one cannot define the
absorption cross section for this case
because we have zero-flux of  for
de Sitter wave propagation. Instead, we may  follow the black hole approach to obtain
the absorption cross section.   If we assume an unknown normalization
, then  may be determined by referring
the absorption cross section for  the low-energy -wave.
In this way the absorption cross section in three dimensions may be defined
by
_abs ^D=3 = A _3   =
[4l A_3^2 H_3 ] _-l, ^2
where
_-l, ^2=(1+)^2(il)^2  
[(+ il + h_+)/2)]^2
[(+ il + h_-)/2]^2 .
Here  is obtained by replacing  by  at
.

For D=4 de Sitter space, one may have
_abs ^D=4 = A _4 ^2  =
[4^2 l A_4^2 H_4 ] _-l, ^2.
However, this approach based on the calculation of the black hole-greybody factor
 leads to a wrong result  to find the absorption cross
section for the cosmological horizon.
Actually there is no   wave propagating truly along
""axis-direction. As is shown in Eq.(), the
incident (ingoing) wave is totally reflected to give the reflected (outgoing) wave
by the approximate potential step at . This is confirmed by the
zero flux of .

discussion 
We study the wave equation for  a minimally coupled massive scalar
 in D-dimensional
de Sitter space. We compute the absorption cross section
 to investigate  its cosmological horizon in the southern diamond.
By analogy of the quantum mechanics of the wave scattering under the potential step,
 it is found that there is no
absorption of a scalar wave in  de Sitter space in the
semiclassical approach.
This means that de Sitter space is usually stable and  in thermal
equilibrium, unlike the black hole. The cosmological horizon not
only emits radiation but also absorbs that previously emitted by
itself at the same rate, keeping the curvature radius of de Sitter space
fixed. This can be proved by the relation of 
 and . This exactly
coincides with the wave propagation of the energy  under the
potential step with  which shows the classical picture of
what the particle goes on. Here we find a nature of the eternal de
Sitter horizon, which means that
its cosmological constant  remains
unchanged, as like the eternal black hole in anti de Sitter
space.


